passages.text: Morgan Stanley | RESEARCH August 29, 2025 07:00 AM GMT
Week Ahead in Latin America | NorthAmerica

We do a deep dive into Chile's core service inflation. In Brazil, debate on the income tax bill continues. In Mexico, inflation and activity data suggests further easing ahead. In Argentina, confidence weakens amid FX depreciation and likely unpopular vetoes. Colombia's tax reform discussions start.
Brazil | IPCA- 15 higher than expected; discussion on income tax bill continues; 2Q GDP data next week

- IPCA-15 was \(-0.14\%\) m-o-m in August (vs \(0.33\%\) in July), above our and market expectations, reaching \(4.95\%\) y-o-y. Overall inflation is easing but groups most linked to monetary policy remain relatively resilient, especially services.- The income tax exemption bill is still under discussion at the Lower House without a clear calendar for its voting. The opposition is pressuring to overturn the compensatory measures which is likely delaying the approval process. There may be some dilution of the compensatory measures, but expectation is that most will be approved together with the income tax exemption according to political analysts. Overall, the bill is likely to be fully approved end November/start December.- Next week, we expect 2Q GDP to rise \(0.5\%\) q-o-q sa and \(2.3\%\) y-o-y (Tuesday) driven by a mild deceleration in private consumption, still sustained by a strong labor market. Focus also on industrial production for July (Wednesday). On the political side, focus on the beginning of former president Jair Bolsonaro's trial (Tuesday). The full trial is scheduled to end by 12 September.

- Further easing ahead. With our US team now expecting Fed cuts starting in September, we revised our Mexico rate path lower and see Banxico continuing its gradual easing cycle, with 25bp cuts in September, November, and December - ending 2025 at \(7.0\%\) and reaching a terminal rate of \(6.50\%\) by March 2026. A majority of board members seem to support further easing, mostly on the back of MXN stability and a widening negative output gap.- 1H/August CPI printed at \(-0.02\%\) , while core inflation was at \(0.09\%\) , both below consensus. The Mexican economy is avoiding recession fears, as the economy grew \(0.6\%\) q-o-q. Agriculture contracted by \(2.4\%\) q-o-q, while services \((+0.8\%)\) and industry \((+0.7\%)\) portrayed some resilience.- While 2Q25 FDI remained stable at \(1.6\%\) of GDP, Mexico's external position showed mild deterioration, with the current account posting a small deficit
For important disclosures, refer to the Disclosure Section, located at the end of this report.
of \(0.1\%\) of GDP on a 4Q rolling basis. The non- oil trade surplus continues to rise, likely benefiting from the front- loading of US imports and subdued domestic demand.

- Today, our focus is on the quarterly inflation report, with the accompanying press conference likely to shed light on the board's current stance. We also have July's public sector balance, which should remain consistent with the solid fiscal performance seen so far this year. Looking ahead to next week, we will be watching key activity indicators: August's PMIs and July's remittances (Monday), August's consumer confidence (Wednesday), formal employment (Thursday), as well as June's private consumption and investment proxies (Thursday).

- Confidence indicators are weakening 
- August's consumer confidence fell \(13.5\%\) m-o-m, while confidence in the government dropped \(13.9\%\) m-o-m, reaching the lowest levels since the start of the current administration. We think the presidential vetoes on pension hikes (and other bills approved on Congress) and the ARS depreciation in late July are likely behind the fall in sentiment.- The government is maintaining a really tight monetary stance ahead of the October election. The BCRA raised reserve requirements for the third time this month to help control FX within bands and sustain disinflation. This tight monetary stance should weigh on activity in 3Q25.- The lower house passed bills to increase funding for public universities and hospitals, with a combined estimated fiscal cost of \(\sim 0.2\%\) of GDP. The government is expected to veto the measures, as they could impose risks to fiscal balance going forward.- Next week, focus will be on August's tax revenues data (Monday), where we expect a positive print given the recent upward trend in revenues.

- Recent polls in Chile show Jose Antonio Kast maintaining a lead in presidential voting intentions, with support ranging from \(28\%\) to \(30\%\) , while Jeannette Jara follows closely at \(25 - 28\%\) . Evelyn Matthei consistently receives around \(14\%\) , Franco Parisi \(9 - 11\%\) , and Johannes Kaiser \(7 - 8\%\) . Runoff scenarios across Criteria Agenda, Panel Ciudadano, and Cadem surveys place Kast ahead of Jara by margins of \(12 - 19\) percentage points. Matthei also - outpaces Jara in simulated contests, with all candidates' support showing minor fluctuations over recent measurements.- Moody's expects Chile's tradition of fiscal prudence to continue following Grau's appointment as Finance Minister. The agency forecasts the fiscal deficit to fall to \(2.2\%\) in 2025 and rise to \(2.7\%\) in 2026, above Treasury targets. The incoming minister outlined priorities for the administration's final phase and reaffirmed commitment to fiscal responsibility and aims to submit the 2026 Budget Law by late September, anticipating parliamentary approval. We do not anticipate sudden changes in policy direction from here.

- The IMF has confirmed a USD 13.8 bn Flexible Credit Line (Tricile, underscoring the strength of its economic policies and safeguards. Authorities plan to reduce access gradually based on risk assessments. We think this is a step in the right direction as the country rebuilds its own reserves buffers to more adequate levels. 
- Next week, the main focus will be in the (Monday) and the trader's survey (Thursday).

- The government said the tax reform draft will be announced today. The draft aims to raise COP\(26.3 bn and use these proceeds to help finance the national budget of COP\)556.9 bn, and the plan includes changes to VAT on high-consumption products, taxes on tobacco, alcohol, carbon, consumption, online gambling and churches, as well as higher income and wealth taxes, with the aim of making the tax system more progressive. Given the increasing funding needs and with elections approaching, we see the odds of passing as rather low and we do not rule out the executive, once again, resorts to approving the budget by decree, putting even more stress on fiscal accounts.- The lower house approves session minutes correcting pension reform procedure. The approved minutes confirm quorum requirements were met, allowing the Constitutional Court to review the law's constitutionality.- Next week, the most important data release will be August CPI. We are expecting 0.16% m-o-m, slightly below consensus estimates for 0.20% m-o-m. This print, however, does not change our view of limited progress on the inflation front into year-end, setting a higher bar for BanRep easing.
Exhibit 1: Chile: Non-volatile (core) service inflation (% m-o-m, SA)
Source:INE,BCCh,Morgan Stanley LatAm Economics
disinflation story for two important reasons:

- Qualitative reason - The recent acceleration in core services is only driven by a few items. By abstracting from understanding the macroeconomic drivers and just looking at the components, we find that while service inflation has come out higher than expected (Exhibit 4), if we exclude telecommunication services (4.5% of CPI) and health services (5.4% of CPI), the rest of services (25.2% of the basket) remains mostly in line with historical patterns (Exhibit 5). Moreover, if we dig even deeper at the subclass level, we find that a large part of the increase is due to dentistry services (subclass 6211), medical services (subclass 6221), telecommunications pack (subclass 8231) and online subscriptions (subclass 8241). These four subclasses represent close to 5.6% of overall CPI. This means the increase in core services is not generalized and is only driven by very few items.
Exhibit 4: Chile: Core services (35.1% of CPI) - seasonal profile (% m-o-m)
Source:INE,BcCh,Morgan Stanley LatAm Economics
Exhibit 5: Chile: Core services excl. telecom services and health services (25.2%) - seasonal profile (% m-o-m)
Source:INE,BcCh,Morgan Stanley LatAm Economics

- Macro reasons - These subclasses do not seem to be driven by higher labor costs. While it is easy to establish a link between non-volatile service inflation and wage growth, when we use a synthetic index built from the above-mentioned subclasses (Exhibit 6), the relation remains unclear. In fact, by running a simple regression between our synthetic service inflation index against lagged wage growth and some seasonal dummies, coefficients are not significant (Exhibit 7). In contrast, core services as an aggregate has a strong link with wage growth, with the model explaining roughly 3/4 of overall core services CPI, while it is only able to explain 10% of the large increase in our synthetic service index (Exhibit 8 and Exhibit 9). These increases cannot be related to rising wages and should normalize in the coming prints.
Exhibit 6: These subclasses have increased beyond historical standards in the last three months
Source:INE,BcCh,Morgan Stanley LatAm Economics

What are the monetary policy implications for BCCh? We think the recent surprises in service inflation should not derail the disinflation story, and hence BCCh easing, but they are still surprises and while we cannot attribute them to higher labor costs, it may raise some red flags for BCCh. In fact, the latest national accounts release for 2Q25 services posted a 1.1% q-o-q increase, up from 0.5% in the previous in quarter. With consumption likely benefitting from a higher wage mass, based on this analysis, we find that this is not translating into higher core service inflation, but this does not mean it may not happen in the future. We anticipate BCCh to adopt a more cautious tone going forward, increasing the risks to our BCCh call to the upside. At the same time, given the dovish comments from Fed chair Powell in Jackson Hole, opening the door for a September cut, we think that on net, BCCh should be able to comfortably deliver \(2 \times 25\) bp cut through year end, as we currently expect.
